  "title": "Rationality",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "72b130e05b871c4f",
      "text": "The question which logic and mindset is at work when we act, has been central to Western intellectual culture. We strangely defer to this as \"rationality\". But \"rational\" and \"irrational\" are  meaningless with respect to our subjective goals, and even more with respect to human interaction in complex, adaptive socio-ecological systems. \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "865119a09ec4ff78",
      "text": "<blockquote>\nIt is not about how people produce things but how people think about the world. — Max Weber\n</blockquote>"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "073bbd4540fb50a0",
      "text": "# Types of Rationality "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "23ad178c936337f2",
      "text": "In economic literature there are different ideas of rationality connected to different ideas we have about how we are as human beings. In other words: a logic of action (rationality) comes along with a certain type of human being supposed to be actually existing. Let's have a look at a few of them: \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a7a26cac5488b179",
      "text": "￭ Neoclassic (i.e. mainstream) economists portray human beings as homo economicus. The homo economicus typically acts in a selfish way according to an utilitarian cost-benefit analysis. His (sic!) actions are focussed on more efficiency and maximizing individual benefits. A homo economicus is supposed to find itself constantly comparing, measuring and calculating - seemingly trapped in a [[calculative rationality]], which is short-term and usually unconcerned with historical or long-term relationships.  \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "78f4c33c02b24c1c",
      "text": "[[Calculative rationality]] is certainly present, also in the commons. But is it dominant? \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8c79c6801aa90362",
      "text": "￭  The mindset of critical institutionalism, which is focused on process, context and reflection, has been called [[practical reasonableness]].  It goes beyond a calculative rationality taking a broader perspective on a given situation and institutional realities.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ab95f1bc6c75cd2d",
      "text": "￭  In socio-ecological economy the basic assumption is, that we are homo socio-ecologicus. Its mindset reflects the long-term perspective for sustaining socio-ecological systems and co-evolutionary processes/factors that are “above and beyond” any individual organism. The rationality of an homo socio-ecologicus recognizes contingency, unpredictable disruptions and the interconnectedness of all living things in a larger pluriverse. In short, there is connection, reflexion and communication among all the elements that belong to a system. They co-determine the way we act (see: \"kommunikative Vernunft\" - Habermas).  \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8f2ab620a59ed702",
      "text": "￭  typical for feminist approaches to economy is a combination of practical, communicative and emotional rationality; so that sensing/ feeling nurtures our reasons for acting\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "fe5be53deb13adae",
