        "text": "# Types of Rationality \nIn economic literature we find different ideas of rationality connected to different ideas we have about how we are as human beings as well as to different methodologies. For instance: \n- Dominant neoclassic economists, that is mainstream ecoonomists, portray us as homo oeconomicus, who typically act according to an utilitarian cost-benefit analysis, focussed on more efficiency and maximizing individual benefits. We are supposed to find ourselves constantly comparing, measuring and calculating and therefore call it [[calculative rationality]]. It is a short-term rationality focused on transactions and usually unconcerned with historical or long-term relationships.\n[[Calculative rationality]] is certainly present, also in the commons. But does it need to be dominant? Luckily, there are other rationality concepts. \n"
