        "id": "4186ffc3e296f125",
        "text": "- In socio-ecological economy there is a basic assumption that we are homo ecologicus or/and sociologicus (a term introduced by German Sociologist Ralf Dahrendorf in 1958). It reflects the holistic, long-term perspective of socio-ecological systems that are “above and beyond” any individual organism.  It recognizes the influence of contingent factors, unpredictable disruptions, the embedded relationality among all living things in a larger, interconnected pluriverse. In short, there es connection and communication among all the elements that belong to a system  \"communicative rationality\". Reflexion an communication co-determines the way we act.  (not sure this is a good translation, it's an Habermas term, \"kommunikative Vernunft\",  where reflexion of the social interaction determines the rationality of action\n    typical for ecological economics (homo oecologicus) is a processual, co-evolutionary and contingent (? ergebnisoffen) rationality, where the embededness, our being part of socio-ecological systems that are \"beyond and above us\" is taken into account\n    typical for feminist approaches to economy is a combination of practical, communicative and emotional rationality; so that sensing/ feeling nurtures our reasons for acting\n    and finally: I'd say what we need to put forward in a context of a commons-oikonomy (or you name it) is a combination of the latter connected to the idea of a human being as a nested-I; so an communicative, contingent and emotional rationality aware if it's context and interdependency of others and of the ecosystem: one could call it an ubuntu-rationality concepts I've dealt  with in an academic work I've done, so - I translate tech terms and then we can try to find a more accessible language for the idea: please edit this as you see fit and then I integrate it into the wiki\n\n    typical for neoclassic economy is a cost-benefit rationality -> directed towards raising efficiency and maximizing individual-benefit/gain)  and tied to the idea of homo oeconomicus  --> we could call it \"calculative rationality\"\n    typical for critical institutionalism is a processual rationality -> where reflexion is key, context and process are taken into account and the human being is dowed with the capacity to put its reasoning beyond the calculative rationality in a given/practical/institutional context; sometimes it's called \"practical reasonableness\"\n    typical for  a practical approach to socio-economy is the \"communicative rationality\" (not sure this is a good translation, it's an Habermas term, \"kommunikative Vernunft\",  where reflexion of the social interaction determines the rationality of action\n    typical for ecological economics (homo oecologicus) is a processual, co-evolutionary and contingent (? ergebnisoffen) rationality, where the embededness, our being part of socio-ecological systems that are \"beyond and above us\" is taken into account\n    typical for feminist approaches to economy is a combination of practical, communicative and emotional rationality; so that sensing/ feeling nurtures our reasons for acting\n    and finally: I'd say what we need to put forward in a context of a commons-oikonomy (or you name it) is a combination of the latter connected to the idea of a human being as a nested-I; so an communicative, contingent and emotional rationality aware if it's context and interdependency of others and of the ecosystem: one could call it an ubuntu-rationality "
