        "text": "# Types of Rationality \nIn economic literature there are different ideas of rationality connected to different ideas we have about how we are as human beings. In other words: a logic of action (rationality) comes along with a certain type of human being supposed to be actually existing. Let's have a look at a few of them: \n- Dominant neoclassic economists, that is mainstream ecoonomists, portray us as homo oeconomicus. The homo oeconomicus typically acts in a selfish way according to an utilitarian cost-benefit analysis. His (sic!) actions, are focussed on more efficiency and maximizing individual benefits. So, we are supposed to find ourselves constantly comparing, measuring and calculating - we seem to be trapped in a [[calculative rationality]]. It is a short-term rationality of economic transactions and usually unconcerned with historical or long-term relationships.  \n[[Calculative rationality]] is certainly present, also in the commons. But is dominant? \n"
