      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "073bbd4540fb50a0",
        "text": "# Types of Rationality \nIn economic literature there are different ideas of rationality connected to different ideas we have about how we are as human beings. In other words: a logic of action (rationality) comes along with a certain type of human being supposed to be actually existing. Let's have a look at a few of them: \n- Dominant neoclassic economists - mainstream economists - portray us as homo economicus. The homo economicus typically acts in a selfish way according to an utilitarian cost-benefit analysis. His (sic!) actions are focussed on more efficiency and maximizing individual benefits. Such a person is supposed to find itself constantly comparing, measuring and calculating - seemingly trapped in a [[calculative rationality]], which is short-term and usually unconcerned with historical or long-term relationships.  \n[[Calculative rationality]] is certainly present, also in the commons. But is it dominant? \n"
