        "id": "073bbd4540fb50a0",
        "text": "# Types of Rationality \nIn economic literature there are different ideas of rationality connected to different ideas we have about how we are as human beings. In other words: a logic of action (rationality) comes along with a certain type of human being supposed to be actually existing. Let's have a look at a few of them: \n- Neoclassic (i.e. mainstream) economists portray human beings as homo economicus. The homo economicus typically acts in a selfish way according to an utilitarian cost-benefit analysis. His (sic!) actions are focussed on more efficiency and maximizing individual benefits. A homo economicus is supposed to find itself constantly comparing, measuring and calculating - seemingly trapped in a [[calculative rationality]], which is short-term and usually unconcerned with historical or long-term relationships.  \n[[Calculative rationality]] is certainly present, also in the commons. But is it dominant? \n"
      },
      "date": 1495318309538
    },
    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "4186ffc3e296f125",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "4186ffc3e296f125",
        "text": "- In socio-ecological economy the basic assumption is, that we are homo socio-ecologicus. Its mindset reflects the long-term perspective for sustaining socio-ecological systems and co-evolutionary processes/factors that are “above and beyond” any individual organism. The rationality of an homo socio-ecologicus recognizes contingency, unpredictable disruptions and the interconnectedness of all living things in a larger pluriverse. In short, there is connection, reflexion and communication among all the elements that belong to a system. They co-determine the way we act (see: \"kommunikative Vernunft\" - Habermas).  \n    "
      },
      "date": 1495318623745
